            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                        <date>July 10</date>
                        <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>I have much pleasure in informing you that the work you refer to was published, under the following title. “The structure &amp; distribution of Coral Reefs 1842, Smith, Elder &amp; Co London.”—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am not sure whether it is now sold separately or only bound up with two other little geological Treatises, also published by the same Firm.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
                        <p>Pray do not think about the postage, as I have pleasure in answering your query.—</p>
                        <p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year range is established by the headed notepaper, which is of a sort that CD used between 1872 and 1874, and by the fact that CD does not mention the <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1572.xml">second edition of <hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref>, which appeared in May or June 1874 (<hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 22, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9475.xml">letter from G. H. Darwin, 30 May 1874</ref>).</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1571.xml"><hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref>.</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8001.xml"><hi rend="italic">Volcanic islands</hi></ref> (published in 1844) and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref> (published in 1846) were reissued by Smith, Elder with <hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi> in a single volume in 1851 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2805.xml"><hi rend="italic">Geology of the ‘Beagle’</hi></ref>).</note>
            </div>
        
